{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17506016","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17506016"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:39:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:39:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2510"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2510","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2510"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.53,0.02,0.23,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2510"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101997"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2510","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2510"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2510"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84447"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"593"},{"type":"tags","id":"1540"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"12802"},{"type":"tags","id":"12807"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2327"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2333"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6476"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7767"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35471"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43171"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101997","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101997"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 36-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a three-hour history of heavy vaginal bleeding and cramping lower abdominal pain. She is primigravida at nine weeks gestation. For the past three days she has had vaginal spotting which was investigated with a transvaginal ultrasound two days ago that showed a healthy, intrauterine pregnancy. Her medical history includes a 10 pack-year smoking history. She takes folic acid and a multivitamin, and has no other significant medical history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears pale and worried. Her pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 80/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, and temperature 37.1 \u00b0C. On speculum examination, there is active bleeding through a dilated cervix with an estimated blood loss of 350 mL and ongoing heavy bleeding seen through the os. Bimanual examination reveals a fundal height consistent with an eight week gestation and a 2 cm dilated cervix. After intravenous fluid resuscitation with one litre of normal saline, her blood pressure improves to 105/72 mmHg.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Misoprostol therapy","Suction dilation and curettage","Methotrexate therapy","Follow-up pelvic ultrasound","Repeat beta-hCG in 48 hours"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with heavy vaginal bleeding and a dilated cervical os in the first trimester, which is diagnostic of an \u003Cstrong\u003Einevitable miscarriage\u003C/strong\u003E. The patient is showing signs of haemodynamic compromise, with tachycardia, initial hypotension, and significant blood loss (350 mL with ongoing bleeding). Therefore, attention must focus on resuscitation and control of bleeding. Apart from prompt intravenous fluid administration, urgent surgical evacuation of products of conception is required to minimise further blood loss. \u003Cstrong\u003ESuction dilation and curettage\u003C/strong\u003E is a controlled method of quickly and safely removing products of conception from the uterus to control bleeding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA threatened miscarriage presents as vaginal bleeding; it may resolve spontaneously, or progress to inevitable, incomplete or complete miscarriage. In this case, the open cervical os and heavy bleeding indicate that the miscarriage is inevitable. Miscarriage can be managed through expectant, medical or surgical management. Expectant management involves \u003Cstrong\u003Efollow-up pelvic ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Erepeating beta-hCG in 48 hours\u003C/strong\u003E; however, this is not indicated in this case of inevitable miscarriage with haemodynamic compromise and significant bleeding. Additionally, prolonged expectant management has an increased risk of infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMedical management involves pharmacological \u003Cstrong\u003Etherapy\u003C/strong\u003E with \u003Cstrong\u003Emisoprostol\u003C/strong\u003E to medically evacuate retained products of conception in inevitable or incomplete miscarriages. This process can take several days and might be appropriate where blood loss is minimal and there are no signs of haemodynamic instability. In this case, with significant bleeding and initial hypotension, medical management is not appropriate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMethotrexate\u003C/strong\u003E is not used in the management of miscarriage, but is used in the medical management of ectopic pregnancies. In this case, a recent ultrasound confirmed an intrauterine pregnancy, ruling out an ectopic pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, given the patient\u0027s significant bleeding, haemodynamic instability, and inevitable miscarriage, suction dilation and curettage is the most appropriate next step to quickly control bleeding and stabilise the patient.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Expectant management in miscarriage is not suitable if there is evidence of infection or increased risk of haemorrhage.","Suction dilation and curettage is the most appropriate management for inevitable miscarriage with significant bleeding and haemodynamic instability."],"references":["ACOG Practice Bulletin No. 200 Summary: Early Pregnancy Loss. Obstet Gynecol 2018;132:1311. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30157093/","Sapra KJ, Joseph KS, Galea S, et al. Signs and Symptoms of Early Pregnancy Loss. Reprod Sci 2017;24:502. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5933199/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84447"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2510"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84447","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/84447"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-06T08:42:55+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-06T08:43:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2510"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101997"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationshi